Just a note:

On 10 Apr 94 10:49:51 GMT, goggi@ludd.luth.se (G|ran berg) said:
>> In article <FAIGIN.94Apr8092012@solarium.aero.org> faigin@aero.org (Daniel P. Faigin) writes:
>> Now, at the risk of showing my own folly, let me suggest that
>> machines which use a Harvard-architecture (as opposed to a
>> Von Neuman architecture) really *are* virus proof.  

>> All major desktop computers today use the Von Neuman architecture,
>> where "program" memory and "data" memory live in the same space.
>> This allows for self-modifying code, which I think is a prerequisite
>> for virus propagation.

>> By contrast, the Harvard-architecture (which I think predates the
>> Von Neuman architecture) uses separate "program" and "memory"

I did not say the above; please ensure your attributions are correct BEFORE
posting.

